Introduction to Neural Networks: Plants Seedling Classification

Project #8

Craig Drummond

Context¶

Background and Context¶

In recent times, the field of agriculture has been in urgent need of modernizing, since the amount of manual work people need to put in to check if plants are growing correctly is still highly extensive. Despite several advances in agricultural technology, people working in the agricultural industry still need to have the ability to sort and recognize different plants and weeds, which takes a lot of time and effort in the long term.

The potential is ripe for this trillion-dollar industry to be greatly impacted by technological innovations that cut down on the requirement for manual labor, and this is where Artificial Intelligence can benefit the workers in this field, as the time and energy required to identify plant seedlings will be greatly shortened by the use of AI and Deep Learning. The ability to do so far more efficiently and even more effectively than experienced manual labor could lead to better crop yields, the freeing up of human involvement for higher-order agricultural decision making, and in the long term will result in more sustainable environmental practices in agriculture as well.

Objective¶

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with the University of Southern Denmark, has provided the data containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species. You being a data scientist, need to build a Convolutional Neural Network model which would classify the plant seedlings into their respective 12 categories.

Data Description¶

This dataset contains images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species.

  • The data file names are:

    • images.npy
    • Label.csv

  • Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to numpy arrays and stored in images.npy file and the corresponding labels are also put into Labels.csv so that you can work on the data/project seamlessly without having to worry about the high data volume.

  • The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from an image.

Plant Species¶

  • Black-grass
  • Charlock
  • Cleavers
  • Common Chickweed
  • Common Wheat
  • Fat Hen
  • Loose Silky-bent
  • Maize
  • Scentless Mayweed
  • Shepherds Purse
  • Small-flowered Cranesbill
  • Sugar beet

Question to Answer¶

  1. What CNN (and optional settings and augmentatioins) will achieve the highest accuracy on this image recognition task

plot_images¶

In [7]:
def plot_images(images,labels):
  num_classes=12                                                                  # Number of Classes
  categories=np.unique(labels)   
  keys=dict(labels['Label'])                                                      # Obtaing the unique classes from y_train
  rows = 3                                                                        # Defining number of rows=3
  cols = 4                                                                        # Defining number of columns=4
  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))                                               # Defining the figure size to 10x8
  for i in range(cols):
      for j in range(rows):
          random_index = np.random.randint(0, len(labels))                        # Generating random indices from the data and plotting the images
          ax = fig.add_subplot(rows, cols, i * rows + j + 1)                      # Adding subplots with 3 rows and 4 columns
          ax.imshow(images[random_index, :])                                      # Plotting the image 
          ax.set_title(keys[random_index])
  plt.show()

Labeled_barplot¶

In [9]:
# function to create labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, v_ticks=True, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))
        
    if v_ticks is True:
        plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)

    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Mask all colors exept green¶

In [16]:
l_green = (25, 40, 50)
h_green = (75, 255, 255)
mask = cv2.inRange(img_hsv, l_green, h_green)
kernel = cv2.getStructuringElement(cv2.MORPH_ELLIPSE, (11,11))
mask = cv2.morphologyEx(mask, cv2.MORPH_CLOSE, kernel)

isMasked = mask > 0
clear_image = np.zeros_like(img_resized, np.uint8)
clear_image[isMasked] = img_resized[isMasked]

cv2_imshow(clear_image)

Note:¶

This is the goal, to get all of the backgound out of the equation and then covert what is left of the green color to grayscale to simplify the analyis

Apply Resize, Gaussian Blur, and Mask on a copy of all images¶

In [17]:
# Output a sample of the original images
plot_images(data, labels)
In [18]:
data_copy = data.copy()
preprocessed_data = []
In [19]:
# Loop through all the images in the images array and transform the images to 
# be simpler, smaller, and the correct format

for image in data:
  resized = cv2.resize(image, None, fx=0.5, fy=0.5)
  gb = cv2.GaussianBlur(resized, (3,3), 0)
  hsv = cv2.cvtColor(gb, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
  masked = cv2.inRange(hsv, l_green, h_green)
  masked = cv2.morphologyEx(masked, cv2.MORPH_CLOSE, kernel)
  imgMask = masked > 0
  clearImg = np.zeros_like(resized, np.uint8)
  clearImg[imgMask] = resized[imgMask]
  preprocessed_data.append(clearImg)

preprocessed_data = np.asarray(preprocessed_data)

Notes:¶

We have converted the original image from a color image with a confusing background to a grayscale image with the background removed. The goal of this is to be able to focus on only what is important about the image

The image was also resized to be 1/2 the original to make processing faster

Model 1 : Shrunken Images¶

In [31]:
new_model()
In [32]:
model1 = Sequential()

#Input Layer
model1.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))

# Add MaxPooling an additional convolutional layer and then pooling a second time
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))
model1.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# Flatten
model1.add(Flatten())

# Adding Fully Connected Hidden Layer
model1.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model1.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Output Layer
model1.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

optimizer = Adam()

model1.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

model1.summary()

Data Augmentation¶

train_data_aug = ImageDataGenerator(
                              horizontal_flip = True,
                              vertical_flip = True,
                              height_shift_range = 0.1,
                              width_shift_range = 0.1, 
                              rotation_range=90,
                              shear_range = 0.2,
                              zoom_range = 0.1, 
                              )

training_generator = train_data_aug.flow(X_train_normalized,y_train_encoded,
                                       batch_size=batch_size, 
                                       seed=seed,
                                       shuffle=shuffle)

In [42]:
model2 = Sequential()

#Input Layer
model2.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))
# Add MaxPooling an additional convolutional layer and then pooling a second time
model2.add(BatchNormalization())
model2.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# Add a second convolution layer
model2.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())
model2.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# Add a third convolution layer
model2.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='valid'))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())
model2.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# Flatten
model2.add(Flatten())

# Adding the first fully connected hidden layer
model2.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))


# Adding a second fully connected hidden layer
model2.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))

# Output Layer
model2.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=0.001)

model2.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

model2.summary()

# Add a second convolution layer
model3.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
model3.add(BatchNormalization())
model3.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# Add a third convolution layer
model3.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu', padding='valid'))
model3.add(BatchNormalization())
model3.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'valid'))

# Flatten
model3.add(Flatten())

# Adding the first fully connected hidden layer
model3.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model3.add(Dropout(0.2))

# Adding a second fully connected hidden layer
model3.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))


# Output Layer
model3.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=0.001)

model3.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

model3.summary()

vgg_new_model = Sequential()

# Add the convolutional part of VGG16
vgg_new_model.add(vgg_model)

vgg_new_model.add(Flatten())

vgg_new_model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
vgg_new_model.add(Dropout(0.2))
vgg_new_model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
vgg_new_model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

optimizer = Adam()

vgg_new_model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

vgg_new_model.summary()

Prediction Confusion Matrix¶

In [80]:
y_pred4_arg=np.argmax(y_pred4, axis=1)
y_test4_arg=np.argmax(y_test_encoded, axis=1)

confusion_matrix4 = tf.math.confusion_matrix(y_test4_arg, y_pred4_arg)
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))
sns.heatmap(
    confusion_matrix4, annot=True, linewidths=.4,
    fmt='d', square=True, ax=ax
)
plt.show()

Notes:¶

  • The vgg16 convolution settings using the color dataset seems to have performed worse than Model2 that used fewer params
  • Class 6 takes the top spot followed closely by Class 3 and then 10 but these are the only classes with more than 90 correct classification
  • Class 4, 0, 9, & 11 have the lowest successfult classifications

Model4 Conclusion¶

  • This model was back to using the color images that had been augmented but the VGG16 concolution portion did not help but actually hurt accuracy

Executive Summary of Analysis¶

Conclusions¶

  1. Of the four CNN models created only Model2 performed well enough for prediction
Model Fit Train Val Test
Model1 - No Augmentation Overfit 75% 65% 61%
Model2 - Augmented data Good 90% 82% 88%
Model3 - Grayscale Good 84% 78% 78%
Model4 - VGG16 Underfit 72% 78% 78%
  1. A CNN with 1 input layer, 2 convolutional layers with batch normalization, maxpolling and dropout (not all together), 2 fully connected layers, and 1 output layer achieved the highest accuract of 88% on unseen test data.
